Elefuga] Α barbarous name sor what we call the pons asinorum, which is explained by Roger Bacon, Op. Text, ii. 21: “Quinta propositio geometriae Euclidis dicitnr Elesuga, id est fuga miserorum.'' This would point to its derivation from the Greek ἔλεος and fuga, but it may perhaps be from the Arabic, just as Dulcamon, a similar term ior the 47th prop, was usually but incorrectly explained as dorthin carnis (cp.
